Part one — shapes.

This notebook has two halves. The first half is about shapes — the five collections you reach for daily, and what each one is good at. The second half is about operations — the higher-order methods that work on all of them, plus the for-yield sugar that desugars into exactly those operations.

In this first half, we will walk through the two parallel collection hierarchies, then look at why immutable does not mean slow, and then meet the five workhorse shapes — list, vector, set, map, and array. We will finish with tuples, which are a natural bridge into the case classes you will meet in notebook five.

The key idea to hold onto is that you choose a shape by how you intend to access it. Build front-to-back and walk recursively, and a list fits. Need indexed access, and a vector fits. Test membership, and a set fits. Look things up by key, and a map fits. Talk to java or to Spark internals, and an array fits. The rest of part one is just filling in why.
